e_map.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(149,1,'2012-09-25 05:30:36','2012-09-25 05:30:36','','MLKJr','','inherit','open','open','','mlkjr','','','2012-09-25 05:30:36','2012-09-25 05:30:36','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/MLKJr.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(150,1,'2012-09-25 05:31:14','2012-09-25 05:31:14','','dorothy','','inherit','open','open','','dorothy','','','2012-09-25 05:31:14','2012-09-25 05:31:14','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/dorothy.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(151,1,'2012-09-25 05:31:17','2012-09-25 05:31:17','','joyce','','inherit','open','open','','joyce','','','2012-09-25 05:31:17','2012-09-25 05:31:17','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/joyce.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(152,1,'2012-09-25 05:31:20','2012-09-25 05:31:20','','maria','','inherit','open','open','','maria-2','','','2012-09-25 05:31:20','2012-09-25 05:31:20','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/maria1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(153,1,'2012-09-25 05:31:22','2012-09-25 05:31:22','','maria2','','inherit','open','open','','maria2','','','2012-09-25 05:31:22','2012-09-25 05:31:22','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/maria2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(810,1,'2013-04-08 20:26:39','2013-04-09 00:26:39','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/schoolapalooza-please-check-out-schoola-org-for-silent-auction-items/schoolapalooza-party-poster-2013/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-811\"><img class=\" wp-image-811 aligncenter\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/schoolapalooza-party-poster-2013_small-300x194.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></a></p>','SCHOOLAPALOOZA! Hope to see you on Friday 26 April 6-10pm at The Clemente Soto Velez Center (corner of Suffolk and Rivington Streets) as we celebrate 20 years of CWS and Maria\'s leadership! Please check out schoola.org for silent auction items.','','publish','open','open','','schoolapalooza-please-check-out-schoola-org-for-silent-auction-items','','','2013-04-08 20:26:39','2013-04-09 00:26:39','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=810',0,'post','',0),(820,1,'2013-04-10 12:57:10','2013-04-10 16:57:10','<strong>                                     The Children’s Workshop School Update\nFor the Month of April 2013\n</strong>                                           http://www.childrensworkshopschool.org\nphone numbers:212-614-9531 or 347-675-9415 or 347-675-9376\n”We’re all a family under one sky!”\n\n<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/820/schoolapalooza-party-poster-2013-4/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-827\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-827\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/schoolapalooza-party-poster-2013_small3-550x356.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"550\" height=\"356\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Schoolapalooza!  Friday 26 April 6-10pm at the Clemente Soto Velez Center on the corner of Rivington and Suffolk Streets, $25 per ticket, celebrating 20 years of The Children’s Workshop School and Maria as founder/principal.</strong> <strong>CWS alumni get in free!</strong>  <strong>Lisa Lisa will perform!  So will The Demolition String Band---and our own music teacher, Terry, singing with her jazz quintet. Great food, courtesy of Stephanie with Dorothy running the wait staff.  Amazing art auction curated by Evan; fantastic silent auction:  a week at a beach house in Costa Rica, designer sunglasses, 2 private yoga sessions, etc. View auction items on the Schoolapalooza web site:  schoola.org.  </strong>\n\n<strong></strong>\nWe will be <strong>selling tickets in the lobby on Fridays before community meeting--buy 2 get one free--</strong>and to <strong>raffle off a Cecile American Girl doll</strong> and other items, what Melissa is calling \"mini-paloozas.\"  Please sign up to <strong>volunteer your time</strong> to help with food and drink service, set up, break down, etc.\n\n<strong>Congrats </strong>to Nixie and family and Wiley and family, winners of the tickets to see The Little Orchestra Society’s production Tubby the Tuba at Lincoln Center.  Thanks to all who took a chance-we raised <strong>$178</strong> for our school.\n\n<strong>Friday Bake/Book Sales</strong>:  Melissa and gang continue to provide great coffee and breakfast treats every Friday before Community Meeting.  Please keep donating books and buying books!\n\n<strong>Thanks to Jen and Nancy for gathering letters to opt-out of InBloom</strong>, a database of your child’s private info which the state is giving out to private educational companies so that they can send promotional materials to you.  The letters will be forwarded to State Education Commissioner King.  To send your letter via email, email Beth at <a href=\"mailto:bcounihan@qcc.cuny.edu\">bcounihan@qcc.cuny.edu</a> and she will email you back the form letter.\n\n<strong>We have Campos--finally!</strong> CWS students will be using the Campos gym/auditorium\n\nGood luck to our 3/4 graders on the state English Language Arts and Math tests.  We know they are well-prepared and confident!  <strong>Dorothy and our teachers will hold a Testing Anxiety talk for parents on Mon 15 April at 8am in the library.\n</strong>\n<strong>TRANQUIL:</strong> View the paintings by CWS mom Ann DeVito, displayed at Gnocco 337 East 10th Street, between A/B.   Half of all sales will go to our school (thanks, Ann!).  Check out Ann’s website at: aqdstudio.com\n\n<strong>JourneyDance with Rachel, our CWS clubs treasurer</strong>:  Rachel will lead morning classes on Mondays and two evening sessions on 9 April and 25 April.  Check out her website at dancewithrachel.com.  Join the JourneyDance gang at the Dance Parade on 18 May!\n\n<strong>Our sympathies to the family of Carol Ray, our recently retired librarian, who passed away last week</strong>.  Carol was a powerful and dynamic woman who led an amazingly socially active and vibrant life:  she marched on Washington with MLK, owned a restaurant on Avenue A and devoted herself to our students and beautiful library, building the collection with her great love of books and learning.  She will be missed by us all.  Details will follow about a CWS community memorial for Carol.\n\n<strong>Week of 1 April:\n</strong>\nWeds 3 April: back to school from Spring Break\nFri 6 April:  Schoolapalooza auction items due-last day\n\n<strong>Week of 8 April:\n</strong>\nWeds 10 April: PTA Executive Board meeting in Library Conference Room after drop off\n\n<strong><em>Friday 12 April: last day to submit school survey:  nycschoolsurvey.org.  also Character Day!  Also:  Arts and Science Fair planning meeting in the lobby after drop off—look for Judy.</em></strong>\n\nWeek of 15 April:\nMon 15 April:  Testing Anxiety meeting for parents in the library at 8am\n\n16, 17, 18 April:  English Language Arts testing for 3, 4, 5 graders\n\n<strong><em>Weds 17 April:  PTA meeting in lobby after drop off</em></strong>\n\nFriday 19 April:  SLT meeting in Suma’s classroom at 7:30am. Patrizia’s Creative Movement/Improvisational Dance Club will perform at Community Meeting.\n\n<strong>Week of 22 April:\n</strong>\n24, 25, 26 April:  Math testing for 3, 4, 5  graders\n<strong><em>Friday 26 April:  Schoolapalooza!\n</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Looking Forward!:</strong>\n\nSave the date and put aside gently worn clothes/toys for the rummage sale:  <strong>The Arts and Science Fair is Saturday 11 May, a fun day for the whole family</strong>—science and art projects, games, face painting, live music and great food.  CWS alumni will run the glob table and the lemon bottle rocket table.  Judy will chair yet again (hugs to Judy)!  Email Judy to help out: garnar-wortzel@att.net\n\n<strong>The 3/4/5 Graders’ Talent Show will be Thursday 13 June</strong>-mark your calendars!\n\n<strong>The Book Fair to benefit our beautiful library will be in June at Barnes and Noble everywhere—just in time to buy Summer Reading books.</strong>\n\n&nbsp;','CWS Update for April 2013:  Schoolapalooza!','','publish','open','open','','820','','','2013-04-10 12:57:10','2013-04-10 16:57:10','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=820',0,'post','',0),(175,1,'2012-09-25 06:24:50','2012-09-25 06:24:50','','CWS-Tee-green','','inherit','open','open','','picture-20','','','2012-09-25 06:24:50','2012-09-25 06:24:50','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Picture-20.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(176,1,'2012-09-25 06:24:51','2012-09-25 06:24:51','','CWS-Tee-red','','inherit','open','open','','picture-21','','','2012-09-25 06:24:51','2012-09-25 06:24:51','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Picture-21.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(177,1,'2012-09-25 06:24:52','2012-09-25 06:24:52','','CWS-Tee-Cyan','','inherit','open','open','','picture-22','','','2012-09-25 06:24:52','2012-09-25 06:24:52','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Picture-22.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(201,1,'2012-09-25 07:03:20','2012-09-25 07:03:20','','pta welcome letter 2012-13','','inherit','open','open','','pta-welcome-letter-2012-13','','','2012-09-25 07:03:20','2012-09-25 07:03:20','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/pta-welcome-letter-2012-13.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(202,1,'2012-09-25 07:05:10','2012-09-25 07:05:10','','pta welcome letter 2012-13','','inherit','open','open','','pta-welcome-letter-2012-13-2','','','2012-09-25 07:05:10','2012-09-25 07:05:10','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/pta-welcome-letter-2012-13.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(736,2,'2012-11-09 12:14:26','2012-11-09 17:14:26','','EmergencyPhone#','','inherit','open','open','','emergencyphone','','','2012-11-09 12:14:26','2012-11-09 17:14:26','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/EmergencyPhone.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(850,1,'2013-05-30 15:29:44','2013-05-30 19:29:44','','BOOK FAIR TO BENEFIT OUR LOVELY LIBRARY!  BARNES AND NOBLE DONATES 20%  WHEN YOU USE CODE #11114907 JUNE 1-8.  See/hear John Carter Cash, son of Johnny Cash, read from his book \"Lupus Rex\" on 1 June at 12:30 at Barnes and Noble Union Square','','publish','open','open','','book-fair-to-benefit-our-lovely-library-barnes-and-noble-donates-20-when-you-use-code-11114907-june-1-8-seehear-john-carter-cash-son-of-johnny-cash-read-from-his-book-lupus-rex-on-1-june','','','2013-05-30 15:29:44','2013-05-30 19:29:44','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=850',0,'post','',0),(468,1,'2012-09-28 05:21:36','2012-09-28 05:21:36','Overview of Curriculum and Expectations\n\nThe 1st and 2nd grade curriculum is both exciting and challenging to the students.\n\n<em>Social Studies:</em>\n\nOur core curriculum alternates each year between two focuses, New York City and Water. Within our curriculum focus of Water we look at the various forms of water, weather, the water cycle, major bodies of water in and around New York, and the aquatic life that thrives in them. To help lay the framework for this, we begin with the basics of water - What is it? Students explore water through hands-on activities and experiments to help draw conclusions about the substance and it\'s various forms. We also extend these understandings into an exploration of how it is important to the survival of people, plants, and animals. The students will work with Pat in the Science room as well, conducting experiments and drawing conclusions as scientists. We will center our field trips on searching for water sources around New York City, and visiting places like gardens, and the Coney Island Aquarium to observe water as a habitat and a part of the city. We will also spend time talking about transportation, bridges, tunnels, and the island of Manhattan. These trips are a wonderful hands-on way for children to truly experience this great city. During our New York City curriculum we launch our study of the city by discussing some landmarks we have seen as well as some that we would like to visit. Our study is neighborhood based and we will focus on various neighborhoods through the city to study. To help lay the framework for this, we begin with a neighborhood walk of the East Village, a neighborhood familiar to all our students. We take neighborhood walks of the surrounding area and document our noticings with maps. To help the students develop their map skills, we begin by creating maps of our classroom and our school. The Lower East Side is home to many parks, gardens and markets that each of the classes visits and shares information about. Some of the other neighborhoods our classes study and visit are China Town, Little India, Little Italy and Harlem. Field trips and visits to these locations are a vital component to support our curriculum. In addition, we further our study by taking a closer look at New York City’s Transportation System, the Markets of New York City and also the bridges and tunnels that connect all of the boroughs to surrounding land. These trips are a wonderful hands-on way for children to truly experience this great city.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Reader’s Workshop:</em>\n\nReader’s Workshop focuses on students developing good reading habits. Each workshop usually begins with a mini-lesson and is followed by students reading independently, with a partner, or in small groups. During this time, teachers hold reading conferences with students in order to meet individual needs. We work with each student to develop reading skills, learn new reading strategies, and choose appropriate books so that children are able to read successfully and with confidence. As we confer with students, we make formal and informal assessments of their reading behaviors so as to inform instruction. It is expected that students choose books from the leveled library and read independently. Students are also expected to read with their reading partners and discuss books at length. Our work in Reader’s Workshop is broken into several components.\n\nThese include:\n\n<em>Read Aloud</em>: A time when students can listen to a story read to them by the teacher. The teacher will ask comprehension questions throughout the book.\n\n<em>Shared Reading</em>: The teacher and the students read a big book, poem or song together. This is an excellent time for students to practice the reading strategies that they are learning.\n\n<em>Partner Reading</em>: Partner reading gives the students the opportunity to read together and to learn from each other.\n\n<em>Guided Reading</em>: This will take place in small groups of 3-5 students. The teacher will choose a text at a suitable level for all the group members. The work in guided reading takes place when the other students are reading independently.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Writer’s Workshop:</em>\n\nThe goal of Writer’s Workshop is to both meet each student’s individual needs and to stretch their ability as writers. Each day starts with a mini-lesson that leads into active writing and illustrating and concludes with children sharing their work with the class. Students are encouraged to use inventive spelling to put their thoughts and ideas into writing. This helps them to take risks as a writer. Students grow a more firm foundation of the writing process so that they can follow an organized plan each time they create a piece of writing. While the students are writing independently, teachers conduct writing conferences with individual students as well as small groups. Conference time is used to assist students in the process of writing as well as providing the skills and strategies they need to become better writers. When our classes publish a new piece of writing we invite our families and school community to come celebrate our work as authors!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Math Workshop:</em>\n\nAs part of our Math curriculum, students are broken up into smaller groups to fit their needs. There are two math groups for each grade level, which provides small class sizes in math and therefore more individualized instruction. Math is a time where students are expected to construct meaning about numbers and how they work through a variety of hands-on activities. We use a curriculum called TERC (Technical Education Research Centers), known as Investigations. The TERC curriculum helps provide students with the opportunity to learn in an environment that stresses making sense of mathematics, building on the ideas that they already have, and learn about new ideas that they have never encountered. This is done through the use of hands-on manipulatives and small group games.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Science:</em>\n\nWorking with our Science teacher Pat, students look at New York City with a scientific eye. Each of the 1st and 2nd grade classes explores different and exciting things both in their classrooms and in the Science Room. Our classrooms are all equipped with Foss Kits, containing hands-on science activities. Making the curriculum connection across subject areas lays the groundwork for an enriched New York City Study. For a more detailed explanation of our Science work, please look at our Science curriculum write up.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Word Study:</em>\n\nStudents exploring the sounds and letters that help create words. We begin with a focus on the classroom word wall. The words wall is also a tool that students will use in their writing. Students can find high frequency and sight words that they might use in their writing. Each week, five words will be added to the wall. The main program we will use to supplement our word study work is Words Their Way for First and Second grade. This program allows children to engage in hands-on activities while learning about letters, sounds and words.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Choice Time:</em>\n\nChoice Time is a portion of our daily schedule where students make new discoveries through academic and social play. During this time students make independent choices and steer their own learning. The children go off to a specific area of the classroom and work cooperatively with a small group of their peers to achieve a learning task. Some Choice Time activities include:\n\nBlocks Art\n\nLegos Painting\n\nPuzzles Chess\n\nGames Listening Center\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/1st2ndcurriculum2012-13.pdf\">Click here for a downloadable PDF&gt;&gt;</a>','1st & 2nd Grade','','publish','open','open','','1st-2nd-grade','','','2012-09-28 05:21:36','2012-09-28 05:21:36','',444,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?page_id=468',0,'page','',0),(475,1,'2012-09-28 05:57:23','2012-09-28 05:57:23','<strong>3rd Grade</strong>\n\n<strong>Overview of Curriculum and Expectations</strong>\n\n<strong><em>Personal Growth and Work Habits:</em></strong>\n\nIn 3rd grade, behaviors relating to personal growth and work habits are crucial to students’ academic and social success. Students are expected to behave respectfully towards children and adults at all times, and to handle conflicts in a peaceful and tolerant manner. During independent work, students must focus on the task at hand and strive to increase their stamina and ability to try new tasks. They are often asked to work with other children in partnerships and small groups, and must learn to take turns, listen attentively to others’ opinions, and be responsible for their share of group work. During whole class times, students must listen to each other and to their teachers, and participate appropriately. Students are given many opportunities to make choices in their work at school, and are expected to make choices and reflect on their own behavior in a way that demonstrates respect for their own and other children’s work. In addition to their schoolwork, students are expected to complete their homework in a timely and thorough manner.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><em>Reading:</em></strong>\n\nIn reading workshop in the fall, we focus on stamina and independence as readers. We also work extensively on developing ideas about our reading, and supporting these ideas with evidence and examples. To facilitate this, we jot down notes about reading, and discuss our reading. Students learn many reading strategies, and are encouraged to continue using previously learned strategies to enhance their understanding.\n\nStudents read independently for extended periods, and keep track of their progress in their reading logs. They also share their thoughts in discussion with partners. In addition to independent reading, students also work as reading buddies to younger students, teaching them to understand stories and appreciate books. During daily read alouds, students enjoy higher-level books than they may be ready to read, and practice their skills of developing and discussion ideas.\n\nIn the spring, students continue to consolidate the skills learned in the fall. They practice these strategies during lengthier independent reading times, in which individual students’ needs are addressed in teacher conferences as well as small-group lessons.\n\nIn the spring, we also focus on reading in genres, such as folktales, informational nonfiction, and poetry. Students learn to notice the characteristics of these genres, including setting, characters, use of language, and common plot developments. Students use what they learn in reading in order to write their own versions of each genre.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Speaking and Listening:</em></strong>\n\nStudents are encouraged and expected to express themselves and consider others’ ideas through speaking and listening. There are many opportunities each day, in each subject, for students to share their ideas with the whole class, as well as with partners and small groups. In these contexts, students are expected to be able to follow a discussion and stay on topic, to think about other people’s questions and comments, and to contribute their own questions and comments in a thoughtful and clear manner.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Word Study and Writing Mechanics:</em></strong>\n\nIn addition to studying these skills in Writing Workshop, students are given explicit instruction and practice in writing mechanics. We use a spelling program called Words\n\nTheir Way, in which students notice and practice using spelling patterns. In addition, both in writing workshop and during other times, we work on capitalization, punctuation, and paragraphing. Specific skills include the correct use of quotation marks, commas, and apostrophes, as well as other skills chosen by the teacher to address issues noticed in student writing.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Math – 3</em></strong><strong><em>rd </em></strong><strong><em>Grade:</em></strong>\n\nIn 3rd grade math in the fall, we do in-depth studies of place value, addition, subtraction, and the creation and interpretation of graphs, through the Investigations curriculum.\n\nWithin each topic, the analysis of word problems and the ability to explain one’s own thinking are heavily emphasized, to ensure that students can apply their mathematical knowledge to real-world problems. Students are also expected to attend closely to other people’s ideas, in order to enhance their own understanding. Many strategies are explored for each topic, so that students can find the strategies that work best for them.\n\nIn addition to a strong conceptual understanding of mathematical ideas, students are expected to memorize basic addition and subtraction facts (such as 7+8 and 16-9).\n\nTimely and thorough completion of homework is an important factor in students’ success in math.\n\nIn the spring, we continue to use the Investigations curriculum to study multiplication, division, fractions, measurement, perimeter, and area, as well as more advanced addition and subtraction. Students are still required to analyze problems and situations to figure out how to solve them, and to always show their thinking and write answers to word problems in full sentences. Students listen to each other’s strategies, and often try out strategies that their classmates have developed and shared. Students are expected to learn the times tables (1 to 10) and are quizzed on these on a weekly basis. It is crucial that students continue to practice these facts over the summer, since they are fundamental to 4th grade math.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Social Studies – Native American Focus:</em></strong>\n\nIn the fall, we work on community-building for the first few weeks of social studies.\n\nThrough activities such as creating self-portraits, interviewing each other, and creating rules as a class, we develop a learning community that will support each of us in our work through the year. We then move on to a study of mapping, learning about map reading and map-making with a focus on physical maps that can help us learn about the land we live in, and how it has changed since it was inhabited only by the Lenape Native Americans before 1609. We take trips to sites like Inwood Hill Park to help us better understand what Manhattan was like then.\n\nIn the spring, we begin with a study of Native Americans nowadays. We study different tribes and how their members’ lives have changed over the years. We also discuss and analyze stereotypes in order to learn how to identify and resist them, with regard both to Native Americans and to other groups. We then move on to a study of the Lenapes before European contact. Through integrated work in reading, writing, and social studies, students read, analyze, and write folktales, learning how a culture’s literature can teach us about its history and belief systems. We also do numerous hands-on projects that help the students understand the Lenapes’ material culture and what it is like to make everything that you use on a day-to-day basis. Students weave wampumlike belts, make clay pots according to the traditional coil method, make cornhusk dolls, and sew moccasins. Following our study of the Lenapes, students do research on the traditional cultures of tribes from other environments, such as the Navajos of the\n\nSouthwest. Our social studies work in the spring is enhanced by trips to sites like the American Museum of Natural History and the Mohonk Preserve in the Catskills.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Writing – Native American Focus:</em></strong>\n\nNote: In writing workshop, some of our projects, though not all, relate to our social studies work.\n\nAfter establishing good writing habits, our first major project is a personal narrative.\n\nStudents write many true stories about their own lives, choosing one or two to further develop into more polished pieces. We study strategies such as adding sensory details, using dialogue, paragraphing, and more, to help students increase their repertoire of writing skills. Each skill is then reinforced in subsequent units. After the personal narrative, we work on literary essays. Students learn to summarize stories, articulate ideas about them, and provide examples to back up their ideas.\n\nIn the spring, we work on three major projects. First, students write folktales based on the work they do in reading and social studies to understand this genre. Students go through an organized process to develop characters, settings, and plotlines according to the traditions of folktales, particularly Native American ones. Our second major writing unit in the spring is poetry. After reading a wide variety of poetry and noticing how poets do their work, students write many of their own poems. They each choose several poems to bring to publication, meaning that they go through a revision and editing process to complete them. Finally, students do research, culminating in a written final product, about different Native American tribes around the country. Working in groups, each child studies a nation such as the Inuits, the Navajos, and the Sioux. The students then work individually to further research a topic of interest within their tribe. Final products may include a written report or a computer presentation.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Social Studies – Immigration Focus:</em></strong>\n\nIn alternating years, we do an in-depth study of the history of immigration to New York City, beginning with Dutch colonization in the 1600s. We begin our work by studying our own families’ immigration history. We discuss, map, and graph data collected by each student, giving a picture of our class’s origins all over the globe. We move on to learn about the Age of Exploration and how it led to the founding of New Amsterdam.\n\nThrough field trips, role-plays, art, and writing assignments, students learn about the experiences of typical Dutch immigrants, as well as minority groups such as Jews, Quakers, and enslaved Africans. We then learn about the British colony of New York, with a special emphasis on slavery in New York. Trips to sites like the Wyckoff Farmhouse Museum and the Morris-Jumel Mansion are central to this work.\n\nIn the spring, we continue our exploration of the history of immigration to the United States, and New York in particular. We learn about the Irish Potato Famine and how it led to great numbers of Irish immigrating to the U.S. We also study our own neighborhood in the 1800s, when it was known as Kleindeutschland, due to the large numbers of Germans who settled down here. We learn about their daily lives in New York, and investigate what the neighborhood was like then, compared to what it’s like now. We then move on to study the Ellis Island era of immigration through a variety of experiences. We go on to study how immigration laws have changed over time in the United States, and why. Finally, we learn about present-day immigration through interviews with immigrants. Students study the transcripts of these interviews and make illustrated books depicting the immigrants’ experiences. Trips to sites like Ellis Island, the Tenement Museum, the Museum at Eldridge Street, the Museum of Chinese in America, and El Museo del Barrio are central to the spring semester’s work.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em>Writing – Immigration Focus:</em></strong>\n\nNote: In writing workshop, some of our projects, though not all, relate to our social studies work.\n\nAfter establishing good writing habits, our first major project is a family history picture book. Students research stories from their families through interviews with family members, and choose a story from before they were born (or when they were too little to remember) to learn more about and make into a picture book. Narrative strategies such as the use of strong verbs, and the creation of powerful leads and endings, are taught alongside research strategies. Students next work on an information book on a topic of personal expertise. They learn to categorize and organize information, and how to write non-fiction in an engaging and accurate manner.\n\nIn the spring, we work on three major projects: persuasive letters, poetry, and historical fiction. When working on their letters, students learn to state their opinions clearly and back them up with logical reasons, to divide their writing into paragraphs, and to use standard business-letter format. The poetry unit may be general, may focus on a particular type of poetry, and may also include songwriting. Finally, in our historical fiction unit, students develop research skills in order to incorporate true historical facts into carefully planned fictional stories.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/3rd4thcurriculum2012-13.pdf\">Click here for downloadable PDF&gt;&gt;</a>','3rd Grade','','publish','open','open','','3rd-4th-grade','','','2012-09-28 05:57:23','2012-09-28 05:57:23','',444,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?page_id=475',0,'page','',0),(1078,1,'2013-12-12 13:46:41','2013-12-12 18:46:41','<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1075\" alt=\"craftfair2013b[1]\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/craftfair2013b11-236x300.jpg\" width=\"236\" height=\"300\" />\n\nGet some holiday shopping done at our annual <strong>Winter Craft Fair</strong> this Friday 13 December in the lobby!  Thanks to Bari, Keiko, Rosie and Eric for organizing.\n\nThank you to Cheryl, Bill and Ted from <b>Project Hope</b> for running a Family Preparedness workshop.  They had excellent tips such as have a stash of small bills and copies of your ID in your emergency to-go bag. <b>Thanks to Hope for copying the family emergency planners to go home in backpacks--you can also download it here:</b>  <a href=\"http://www.nyc.gov/html/oem/html/ready/myemergencyplan_guide.shtml\">http://www.nyc.gov/html/oem/html/ready/myemergencyplan_guide.shtml</a>\n\n<b>Don\'t forget Penny Harvest!</b>—<b>Gather up your change (and bills) and send it into school with your children.</b>  We will donate all that we collect from Penny Harvest to a charity still to be determined.  Thank you to Elyssa and Michelle’s class and Crystal’s class for being our Penny Harvest leaders.\n\n<b>Thank you to Barbara and her community at The Shala yoga center for raising $5000 to help fund our Bent on Learning yoga program!</b>\n\n<b>Thank you to all the families who participated in this year’s SCRIP gift card fundraiser!</b> Thanks to you we raised over $1,000 for the school! Thank you for getting your friends, family and work place involved, we really appreciate the effort!! <b>Cards will be available by end of day </b><b>Friday 13 December; please check your email.  </b>Thank you to Tiffany, Marcia and Helen for coordinating the SCRIP fundraiser.<b></b>\n\n<strong>RAFFLES:</strong>\n\n<strong>Win 4 tickets to see The Big Apple Circus at Lincoln Center on New Year’s Day!  $2 per chance/3 chances for $5 -</strong>-tickets sold during Coffee And.. on <b>6 December, 13 December and 20 December-with the</b> <strong>drawing at Community Meeting Thank you to Big Apple Circus for their generous donations of the tickets.</strong>\n\n<strong>Win Saige, the American Girl Doll of the Year for 2013!  $5 per chance/5 chances for $20</strong><strong>  Raffle tickets sold during Coffee And… on 13 December and 20 December with drawing at Community Meeting on 20 December.</strong>\n\n<strong></strong><b>Congrats to Coco</b>—she won 2 tickets to the New York Theatre Ballet’s production of <i>The Nutcracker</i> at Florence Gould Hall.  Thank you to NYTB for their generous ticket donation.\n\n<b>Class news:</b>  The fifth graders are enjoying learning to play golf at Chelsea Piers.  The pre-k kids are going on a field trip to the Eldridge Street Museum and the third graders are looking forward to sharing their How To… books at a Writing Celebration later in the month.  Every grade has visited the fifth graders’ fantastic Civil Rights Museum exhibits.\n\n<b>FUN (and mostly free)STUFF TO DO!:</b>\n\n<b>Vintage Train rides!!</b>—every Sunday in December—Departures from <b>2nd Avenue F train stop</b> are at 10:01 AM, 11:30 AM, 1:01 PM, 2:30 PM, and 4:01 PM. <a href=\"http://www.mta.info/metrocard/promos/Vintagetrain/\">http://www.mta.info/metrocard/promos/Vintagetrain/</a>\n\n<b>9<sup>th</sup> Precinct Annual Children’s Christmas Event</b>—Saturday 14 Dec at 321 East 5 St from 9-1pm—FREE\n\nTuesday 17 December—<b>Holiday Party at NYPL/Tompkins Square Library</b>—4:00-5:30—snacks and performances—FREE\n\n“Circle of Dance” exhibit—<b>National Museum of the American Indian</b>—FREE\n\n<b>“The ABC of It:  Why Children’s Books Matter”</b> exhibit at the New York Public Library main branch, 42<sup>nd</sup> and 5<sup>th</sup> Ave—FREE\n\n<b>Upcoming important dates:</b>\n\n<i>W<strong>eds 18 December—PTA General Meeting—after drop-off in lobby</strong></i>\n\n<strong> 2</strong><b>0 December—Coffee And… to benefit the CWS Band—thanks to Satya for coordinating and raffle drawings for American Girl doll and 4 tickets to The Big Apple Circus on New Years’ Day!  It’s also PAJAMA DAY!</b>\n\n<b> </b><b>Winter Recess</b>:  23 December to 1 January—back to school 2 January 2014!—<b>HAPPY AND SAFE HOLIDAYS TO ALL!</b>\n\n<b>Looking Ahead to January 2014:</b>\n\n8 January—PTA Executive Board meeting\n\n<em>15 January-PTA General Meeting-after drop-off</em>\n\n<b>Thursday 16 January—tentative date:  Martin Luther King All-School Celebration</b>\n\nFriday 17 January-tentative—half-day for professional development\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b> </b>\n\n<b> </b>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Winter Craft Fair and News for December','','publish','open','open','','winter-craft-fair-and-news-for-december','','','2013-12-12 13:46:41','2013-12-12 18:46:41','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1078',0,'post','',0),(1058,1,'2013-11-27 14:04:44','2013-11-27 19:04:44','<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1075\" alt=\"craftfair2013b[1]\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/craftfair2013b11-236x300.jpg\" width=\"236\" height=\"300\" />\n\nGet ready for the <strong>CWS Winter Craft Fair--Friday 13 December--Pipsqueak Chapeau, Photo Booth, Handknits, Ceramics, Original Artwork, Baked Goods, T-shirts of all kinds, Notebooks, Skin Care Items</strong>--and more!  <strong>Cash, check and credit cards accepted!  </strong>Thank you to Bari, Keiko, Rosie and Eric for organizing the Winter Craft Fair.\n\n<strong>RAFFLES:</strong>\n\n<strong>Win 2 tickets to see The New York Theatre Ballet\'s production of <em>The Nutcracker</em></strong> on an available date in mid-December.  <strong>$2 per chance/3 chances for $5.</strong>  Tickets on sale during Coffee And... on <strong>Friday 6 December-</strong>-drawing at Community Meeting same day.\n\n<strong>Win 4 tickets to see The Big Apple Circus at Lincoln Center on New Year\'s Day!  $2 per chance/3 chances for $5 -</strong>-tickets sold during Coffee And.. on 6 December, 13 December and 20 December-with the <strong>drawing at Community Meeting on 20 December.</strong>\n\n<strong>Thank you to New York Theatre Ballet and Big Apple Circus for their generous donations of the tickets.</strong>\n\n<strong>Congrats to Liany and Redding</strong>--they each won a rainbow loom with carrying case and extra rubber bands!\n\n<strong>Thanks to all families who participate in our fundraising efforts</strong> by helping out, or taking a chance with our raffles or buying  books, and Coffee And... before Friday Community Meetings.  <strong>All proceeds go to funding enrichment programs for all CWS students</strong>--everything  from Turtle Bay Music School to the CWS Band to Bent on Learning Yoga.\n\n<strong>Penny Harvest!</strong>--Support Penny Harvest at CWS--send change (bills welcome too) in to school with your child.  Every week, our Penny Harvest leaders from Elyssa and Michelle\'s class and Crystal\'s class will go around to each classroom, collecting all the change.  Our Penny Harvest collection will go to a charity still to be decided.\n\n<strong>Happy Thanksgiving to All!</strong>','Winter Craft Fair-Fri 13 Dec and December Raffles:  Nutcracker and Big Apple Circus','','publish','open','open','','winter-craft-fair-fri-13-dec-and-december-raffles-nutcracker-and-big-apple-circus','','','2013-11-27 14:04:44','2013-11-27 19:04:44','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1058',0,'post','',0),(301,1,'2012-09-25 15:43:34','2012-09-25 15:43:34','','toystory','','inherit','open','open','','toystory','','','2012-09-25 15:43:34','2012-09-25 15:43:34','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/toystory.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(900,1,'2013-07-10 08:16:20','2013-07-10 12:16:20','<p align=\"center\"><strong>The Children’s Workshop School Update</strong></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>For Summer 2013</strong></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><a href=\"http://www.childrensworkshopschool.org/\">http://www.childrensworkshopschool.org</a></p>\n<p align=\"center\">212-414-9531 or <a href=\"mailto:ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org\">ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</a></p>\n<p align=\"center\">”We’re all a family under one sky!”</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Thank you to Rossella, Pierluigi, Ciara and Ilaria, Gianlucca and the staff of Gnocco for hosting Maria’s 20<sup>th</sup> Anniversary Celebration on 20 June-and thanks to Rosie for making the poster!</strong>  Over 100 teachers, administrators, parents, children, alumni, former teachers, and alumni parents gathered to celebrate and hear Maria’s co-founder Jean speak about the early days of CWS.  Gary presented Maria with the giant 20, made by Andrew and signed by all students, teachers and staff.  The kids serenaded Maria with “We’re All a Family Under One Sky” and “Black Socks.”  Maria was surprised and delighted!\n\nCongrats to our fifth graders on their <strong>Moving Up Ceremony</strong>!    <strong>Thank you to Bess, her mom Lisa and Elizabeth for making and sharing the inspiring film “Raise Your Voice.”</strong>  Bess was so affected by the 5th grade study of the Civil Rights Movement that she wanted to make a short film in which her classmates would each choose a word and sentence that represented what the Civil Rights Movement meant to them.  <strong>Thank you to Jessica for creating the yearbook, a great memento featuring each graduate.  Thanks to Joyce, Luis and the fourth grade families for hosting the luncheon afterwards; much thanks to Beverly and her husband Dee for decorating and providing the space for the celebration and to PS34 for lending us their auditorium.</strong>\n\n<strong>Congrats to all the performers in the 3/4/5 Grade Talent Show and thanks to Jessica and Crystal, as always, for organizing and directing. </strong>Everyone enjoyed the show!  Performances ranged from Double Dutch wizardry to the Abbott and Costello routine “Who’s on First?” to songs like “Girls Just Wanna Have Fun” to violin and guitar solos.  Congrats to all the performers!\n\nThank you to Jia Lee, parent and teacher at The Earth School, for meeting with us about the growing concern over high-stakes testing (DOE-mandated K-2 testing is on the horizon).  Julie will post information and resources to our website before school starts in September.  In the meantime, go to <strong>changethestakes.org</strong> for more information.\n\nThank you to Gary, Elizabeth, Tiffany and Judy for coordinating and putting together the <strong>CD of Community Meeting Songs</strong> and to Mario for Tu Casa studios for donating his studio space.  Each class is featured singing their favorite song:  everything from Jaina’s class singing “This Land is Your Land” to Scott’s class singing “When the Rain Comes Down.<strong>”  We will be selling the CDs as soon as school starts for $20 each and will raffle off a CD (almost) every Friday at Community Meeting ($1 per chance).</strong>\n\nThanks to <strong>Chico,</strong> the iconic LES muralist, for coming in to touch up the Under the Sea mural he painted for CWS on the third floor.\n\nWe did not have a<strong> Field Day</strong> this year—Bill, the adaptive physical education teacher, has always been the one to organize it but he was not assigned to our school.  Next year, we will see to it that we have a Field Day, whether we are lucky enough to have Bill or not!\n\nDorothy and Maria have met with Selim Ozalp, the architect who designed our library and he will re-work the space to create a <strong>memorial area for Carol</strong>, our recently-retired librarian who passed away in the Spring and is greatly missed.\n\n<strong>We will have composting of school lunch food scraps starting in the Fall, thanks to Leslie and the Nutrition Committee.</strong>  The compost buckets, once full, will be dumped and buried in The Children’s Garden on the corner of 12<sup>th</sup> and B by our students. CWS  is piloting the program; if all goes as it should, EVCS and The Spectrum School will also compost school lunch in the Spring.\n\n<strong>Thanks to Rina, The Children’s Workshop School is a participant in </strong><strong><em>Schoola Stitch’s Children’s Clothing Drive</em></strong><em>. </em><strong>Your clothing donations benefit our school.  Go to <a href=\"http://www.schoola.com/labs\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.schoola.com/labs</a></strong><strong> to sign up, select Children’s Workshop and request a bag. You will be mailed a postage-paid collection bag which you then fill with gently-used name brand children’s clothing. UPS picks it up free of charge.  Once Schoola Stitch receives the clothing, they sort it, sell it and give up to 40% of the proceeds to our school. On average they are seeing between $30-$50 per bag of clothes donated back to participating schools.  </strong>\n\nThe New York Public Library\'s Main Branch at 42<sup>nd</sup> and 5<sup>th</sup> Ave has a great can’t-miss hands-on exhibit<strong>, The ABC of It:  Why Children’s Books Matter </strong>on view til March 2014.<strong></strong>\n\n<strong>Maria recommends a weekend day trip to Governor’s Island—take the free ferry and explore!  <a href=\"http://www.govisland.com/html/home/home.shtml\">http://www.govisland.com/html/home/home.shtml</a></strong>\n\nIf your child(ren) did not receive a <strong>Summer Reading Journal</strong> from our Barnes and Noble Book Fair (which benefitted our lovely library), download it here: <a href=\"http://img1.imagesbn.com/pimages/kids/summerreading/2013/bnsummertearpad.pdf\">http://img1.imagesbn.com/pimages/kids/summerreading/2013/bnsummertearpad.pdf</a>  When your child reads 8 books, s/he will receive a free book at Barnes and Noble.\n\nHappy and safe summer to all!  <strong>The public pools offer free swimming lessons and give out free breakfast and lunch.</strong>  Text NYCMeals to 877-877 for a full list of breakfast/lunch sites.\n\n<strong>See you on 9 September-and the auditorium should/will be finished!</strong>   Any questions/concerns/ideas please email <a href=\"mailto:ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org\">ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</a>. Teachers will send out their letters at the end of August!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','CWS Summer 2013 Update','','publish','open','open','','cws-summer-2013-update','','','2013-07-10 08:16:20','2013-07-10 12:16:20','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=900',0,'post','',0),(326,1,'2012-09-26 19:37:10','2012-09-26 19:37:10','Weekly Updates Sept 26 2012','Weekly Update 9262012','','inherit','open','open','','childrens-workshop-school-weekly-update-9262012','','','2012-09-26 19:37:10','2012-09-26 19:37:10','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Childrens-Workshop-School-Weekly-Update-9262012.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(1092,1,'2014-01-04 15:21:51','2014-01-04 20:21:51','&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Welcome back to school!</strong>\n\n<strong>Coffee And...Book Sale will resume on Fri 10 January</strong> before Community Meeting, along with the Lego Minecraft Raffle.  Thanks, as always, to Melissa, Natalie, Roxanne, Sayoko, Paul and all those who contribute and consume.\n\n<strong>Saturday 11 January 9:30-3:30—workshop hosted by CEC-1 at the Lower East Side Girls Club with community leaders about District 1 schools, particularly the new school in the works in the Seward Park Urban Renewal Area.</strong> Please see more info on the Community Education Council-District 1 website:  <a href=\"http://cecd1.org/2013/12/10/372/\">http://cecd1.org/2013/12/10/372/</a>\n<h3>THANK YOU to Darryl (Justine and Jane\'s mom), our Mural and Painting Clubs\' teaching artist, for arranging an exhibit of the clubs\' artists at Michael Mut Project Space!\nThe How Do I Love Me? art show will run from January 11th-24th, 2014. Opening reception will be Saturday, January 11th, 4pm-6pm, 97 Avenue C.</h3>\n<strong>Thursday 23 January at 6pm is our All-School Martin Luther King Living the Dream Celebration in the huge auditorium at ICE on 15th Street between 1st and 2nd Avenues!  </strong>Each class will perform, as well as Patrizia\'s Improvisational  Dance Club and Mr. Scott\'s Experimental Dance Group.  This is a beautiful annual event, celebrating 20 years of The Children\'s Workshop School community\'s commitment to Martin\'s vision of peace and social justice.  Thank you in advance to our teachers, Maria, Dorothy, Joyce and our children for their hard work putting on a great show!\n\n<strong>Raffle!:  Win 2 tickets to see<em> Bob Marley\'s Three Little Birds </em>at The New Victory Theater</strong> on an available date in February of the winner\'s choice. Perfect for ages 5 and up.  Tickets sold during Coffee And...Book Sale on Fri 24 January and Fri 31 January, with drawing at Community Meeting on 31 January.  Thank you to the New Victory Theater for their generous donation of the tickets.\n\n<strong>Other Important Dates in January:</strong>\n\nWeds 8 January--PTA Executive Board meeting after drop-off in library conference room\n\nFri 10 January-School Leadership Team meeting in Suma\'s classroom at 7:30am\n\n<strong>Weds 15 January-PTA General Meeting in the lobby after drop-off</strong>\n\n<strong>Friday 17 January--1/2 day</strong> for teacher professional development--dismissal date tba\n\n<strong>Monday 20 January-Martin Luther King Day-no school</strong>\n\n<strong><em>Upcoming Important Dates in February:</em></strong>\n\nWeds 5 Feb:  PTA Executive Board meeting after drop-off in library conference room\n\n<strong>Sat 8 Feb and Sun 9 Feb:  Barnes and Noble Book Fair to benefit our lovely library!  Thanks to Nicole for organizing.</strong>\n\n<strong>Weds 12 Feb--PTA General Meeting--6pm in the lobby--pizza and childcare provided</strong>\n\nWinter Break!:  17-21 February--No School--enjoy!  Back to school on Monday 24 February.\n\n<em><strong>School Tours:  Families interested in The Children’s Workshop School, please email Joyce  (<a href=\"mailto:jborden@schools.nyc.gov\" target=\"_blank\">jborden@schools.nyc.gov</a>)or Dorothy (<a href=\"mailto:dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov\" target=\"_blank\">dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov</a>) to sign up for a  tour.  We look forward to meeting you!</strong></em>\n\n<em><strong>Upcoming  dates:  </strong></em>\n\n<em><strong>Mondays at 8:15am: 6 January, 2014; 27 January 2014; 10 February 2014; 24 February 2014</strong></em>\n\n<em><strong>Fridays at 9:00am:  10 January 2014; 24 January 2014; 7 February 2014 and 28 February 2014.</strong></em>\n\n&nbsp;','Happy New Year!','','publish','open','open','','happy-new-year','','','2014-01-04 15:21:51','2014-01-04 20:21:51','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1092',0,'post','',0),(1105,1,'2014-01-22 13:52:02','2014-01-22 18:52:02','Hello CWS Families,\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDue to the extremely cold temperatures predicted for the evening on Thursday, January 23<sup>rd</sup>, we have decided to cancel our MLK Honoring the Dream celebration.  Making this decision was not an easy one, and it is only the second time in twenty years that we have had to do this, however, the safety and well being of the children, families and staff at our school always comes first.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWe have also taken into consideration the difficulty that some families would face in having to bring children out on such a cold and blustery night.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNever fear – the show will go on! In the coming weeks, we will have presentations of the classes’ MLK performance during Community Meetings.  The schedule of performances is below, we hope you are able to join us as we continue to celebrate Dr. King’s Dream!\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPeace,\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMaria\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>January 31<sup>st</sup></b> –  PreK and K Classes\n\n<b>February 7<sup>th</sup></b> – 1/2 Classes\n\n<b>February 14<sup>th</sup></b> – 3<sup>rd</sup> Grade Classes\n\n<b>February 28<sup>th</sup></b> – 4<sup>th</sup> Grade Classes\n\n<b>March 7<sup>th</sup></b> – 3<sup>rd</sup>/4<sup>th</sup>/5<sup>th</sup> Grade Class and 5<sup>th</sup> Grade Classes\n\n&nbsp;','','','publish','open','open','','1105','','','2014-01-22 13:52:02','2014-01-22 18:52:02','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1105',0,'post','',0),(1109,1,'2014-01-23 15:06:22','2014-01-23 20:06:22','<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Spring Clubs!-</strong>-Thanks to Joyce and Rachel for putting together a great selection of clubs--the listing went home in backpacks.  All the favorites, from Hip Hop to Mural Club to Robotics to Sports Club return, as well as some new clubs: Knitting, Rainbow Loom, Jewelry Making.  Registration is Tues 28 Jan and Weds 29 Jan in the lobby from 7:45-9:00.  Fall Clubs end 7 Feb and Spring Clubs run 10 Feb til 20 June.</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Phone Drive-</strong>-Thanks to Paul, Elizabeth, Tiffany, John, Kevin, Lara, Steve, Maria and Hope for running the phone drive on Mon 27 Jan and Tues 28 Jan in the evening.</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Save the dates!--Saturday 8 February and Sunday 9 February--the CWS Library Book Fair at Barnes and Noble Union Square. </strong> Thanks to Nicole, we have a great line-up of readings:  Victoria Kann, former CWS mom, reading from her latest <em>Emeraldlicious </em>on 9 Feb at 11:30; Madeline Valentine reading her book <em>The Bad Birthday Idea</em> at noon on 8 Feb and many more.</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\">Evening PTA Meeting--Weds 12 February at 6pm in the lobby--childcare provided, thanks to Joyce and Sonia!</span></strong></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><strong> </strong></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\">FUN STUFF TO DO:</span></strong></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Central Park Winter Jam!-</strong>-Saturday 25 jan from 11-3--FREE---cross-country skiing, snowshoeing, learn to ski and snowboard.  Check out <a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=3eeeb8b3c43b4cca8cac07816642a4a2&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.nyc.gov%2fparks%2fwinterjam\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.nyc.gov/parks/winterjam</a></span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>New York Theatre Ballet\'s production of The Alice in Wonderland Follies</strong> at Florence Gould Hall on Saturday 25 Jan at 1:00 or Sunday 26 jan at 11:00, 1:00 or 3:30. 1 hour long-perfect for ages 3-10.  Check out:  <a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=3eeeb8b3c43b4cca8cac07816642a4a2&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.nytb.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.nytb.org</a></span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>New exhibit at The Morgan Library--The Little Prince:  A New York Story--24 Jan-27 Apri</strong>l.  See original drawings and manuscript drafts of Saint-Exupery\'s beloved classic, written while he lived in NYC.</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=3eeeb8b3c43b4cca8cac07816642a4a2&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.themorgan.org%2fexhibitions%2fexhibition.asp%3fid%3d90\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.themorgan.org/exhibitions/exhibition.asp?id=90</a></span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Ongoing at the New York Public Library main branch at 5th Ave and 42nd Street until 23 March:  The ABC of It:  Why Children\'s Books Matter-</strong>-featuring favorites like Goodnight Moon, Alice in Wonderland and A Wrinkle in Time</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=3eeeb8b3c43b4cca8cac07816642a4a2&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.nypl.org%2fevents%2fexhibitions%2fabc-it\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.nypl.org/events/exhibitions/abc-it</a></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Chinese Lunar New Year Parade!</strong>--<strong>Celebrate the Year of the Horse!--Sunday 2 February at 1pm-parade starts on Mott and Hester Streets.</strong></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-family: tahoma;font-size: small\"><strong>Thunderbird Native American Dancers Annual Concert and Pow-Wow at The Theater for the New City, 155 First Avenue--31 January til 9 Feburary.</strong>  Childrens\' matinees on Saturday and Sunday at 3:00</span></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=3eeeb8b3c43b4cca8cac07816642a4a2&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.theaterforthenewcity.net%2fthunder.htm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.theaterforthenewcity.net/thunder.htm</a></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"><em><strong>School Tours:  Families interested in The Children’s Workshop School, please email Joyce  (<a href=\"mailto:jborden@schools.nyc.gov\" target=\"_blank\">jborden@schools.nyc.gov</a>)or Dorothy (<a href=\"mailto:dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov\" target=\"_blank\">dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov</a>) to sign up for a  tour.  We look forward to meeting you!</strong></em></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>\n<div dir=\"ltr\"></div>','Spring Clubs and Book Fair','','publish','open','open','','spring-clubs-and-book-fair','','','2014-01-23 15:06:22','2014-01-23 20:06:22','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1109',0,'post','',0),(1116,1,'2014-01-24 16:07:42','2014-01-24 21:07:42','Since the MLK Celebration was cancelled, today\'s community meeting was a glimps of the children singing all together. It was the first time all grades sang together on the stage. They were super energetic! Happy Singing! (ps. excuse the bad quality of the video. but you can get the idea!) <a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/2014-01-24-09.16.43.mov\">&lt;&lt;&lt;VIDEO LINK HERE&gt;&gt;&gt;</a>','Practicing the MLK celebration all-school-songs','','publish','open','open','','practicing-the-mlk-celebration-all-school-songs','','','2014-01-24 16:07:42','2014-01-24 21:07:42','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1116',0,'post','',0),(1127,1,'2014-01-27 21:35:32','2014-01-28 02:35:32','<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/spring-clubs-2014.pdf\">CLICK HERE &gt;&gt;&gt; FOR Spring clubs 2014 BROCHURE</a>\n\nDear Parents,\nWelcome to a new session of after school clubs! Please take time to read this letter and the clubs list, as there is some new information.\nSPRING SESSION REGISTRATION DATES: TUESDAY, JANUARY 28th &amp; WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 29th. REGISTRATION WILL BE HELD IN THE LOBBY FROM 7:45AM TO 9:00am ON BOTH DAYS. Spring clubs will begin on Monday, February 10th and end June 20th, 2014.\n\nTHERE WILL BE NO BREAK IN BETWEEN FALL AND SPRING CLUBS.\n\nRemember: In order to cover the club\'s expenses, each club MUST have a minimum of 7 children in order for the club to run. Once again, PLEASE FILL OUT ALL NECESSARY FORMS BEFORE COMING TO REGISTRATION. THIS IS EXTREMELY IMPORTANT! This will help the registration process move more quickly.This year, we will add an extra week onto each semester of clubs making each club last 19 weeks instead of 17 as in the past, in order to offer clubs earlier in Mid-September and later in June to accommodate busy parents. Because of that and increasing costs, all clubs will cost $260 for the 19 sessions which makes the cost for each session $13.70. Some clubs require a $10 or $20 materials fee. We will offer a 20% discount to those enrolling in 4 or more clubs.\n\nMAKE CHECKS PAYABLE TO THE CWS PTA. WE ACCEPT CREDIT CARDS AS WELL. DO NOT HAND IN REGISTRATION FORMS TO THE OFFICE! There will be a lottery for clubs that are over enrolled so there is no need to worry about being first at registration. Parents may register for the children of ONE other family in addition to their own. So, if you are unable to make registration for whatever reason, you may ask another parent to register your children for you. A list of the clubs will be displayed at registration so parents will be able to see which clubs are full and which have spaces left.\n\nAs ever, no one should hesitate to join a club for lack of money. If your family needs assistance, contact me or Maria Velez-Clarke. If you have any questions or concerns, you may contact Joyce in the office.\n\nSnack will be provided to all children right after school. Parents or caretakers should pick up their children promptly at 4:45 in the lobby. Please be on time! Club leaders have to leave promptly at 4:45. You also have the option of putting your child in the <a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/EXTENDED-LETTER-FALL-2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">extended day option</a> and pick your child up any time between 4:45 and 5:50pm. Clubs do not meet on half days, school holidays, and parent teacher conference days.<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/EXTENDED-LETTER-FALL-2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> (Click here for detailed pricing for Extended Day&gt;&gt;).</a>\n\nWe are also very pleased to announce that our school secretary, Joyce Borden, and Rachael Frank, a CWS parent will be helping again with the clubs program this year. Many programs are also taught by the CWS teachers and parents. Thank you so much for all the support!\n\nFor alternative options for School Holidays, Green Apple Kids Holiday camp is held at Earth School (Avenue B and 6th Street)  from 8am - 4pm. For more information, please click &gt;&gt;&gt; <a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/community/afterschool-clubs/gak_brochure_3rd_draft-docx/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-943\">Green Apple Kids Brochure 2013-2014</a> and <a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/community/afterschool-clubs/green-apple-kids-mini-camp-application-docx/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-944\">Green Apple Kids Mini Camp Application</a>.\n\nDays of the Green Apple Kids Holiday Camp (23 Days in all)\n\nOctober 14- Columbus Day\n\nNovember 5- Election Day\n\nNovember 11- Veterans Day\n\nNovember 29- Day after Thanksgiving\n\nDecember 23,24,26,27,30,31- Winter Recess\n\nJanuary 20- Martin Luther King Day\n\nFebruary 17,18,19,20,21- Mid Winter Recess\n\nApril 14,15,16,17,18,21,22- Spring Break\n\n&nbsp;','CLUBS REGISTRATION TUESDAY & WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 28 & 29 in the morning!','','publish','open','open','','1127','','','2014-01-27 21:35:32','2014-01-28 02:35:32','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1127',0,'post','',0),(382,1,'2012-09-26 22:06:45','2012-09-26 22:06:45','','favicon','','inherit','open','open','','favicon','','','2012-09-26 22:06:45','2012-09-26 22:06:45','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/favicon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1216,1,'2014-04-16 09:09:16','2014-04-16 13:09:16','<img class=\"size-full wp-image-1215 alignleft\" alt=\"Schoola_call_2014_8-200x300\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Schoola_call_2014_8-200x300.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" />\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1228\" alt=\"artsandsciencefair2014\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/artsandsciencefair2014-230x300.jpg\" width=\"230\" height=\"300\" />\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.seedsofchangegrant.com/uploads/fce15adf-92ec-4e03-a361-9f0438c90c57.jpg\" />\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>Thanks to all members of the CWS community who have donated auction items for Schoolapalooza-30 May at the Clemente Soto Velez Center!  We will have a solicitation day on Fri 2 May--email Tiffany or Rachel if you would like to join a group of parents canvassing the East Village and Williamsburg for restaurant and hotel donations:  zergestiffany@gmail or rachiefrank505@yahoo.com.  See the Schoolapalooza website for the donation letter and auction forms:  http://www.schoola.org</strong></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Saturday 10 May:  The 20th Annual Art and Science Fair!  Email Judy to help out: garnar-wortzel@att.net.  Make food, do facepainting, run a science project table, help in the kitchen, donate handmedowns for the rummage sale.</span></strong>\n<p align=\"center\"><b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">NEW</span></b><b> Parent Survey</b></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><b>This is <span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">NOT</span> the School Environment Survey (Green Envelopes)</b></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><b>That Was Given Out at School.</b></p>\n<p align=\"center\"> <b>Please Click on The Link to Complete This Short Survey</b></p>\n\n<h3 align=\"center\"><a href=\"http://twitter.us3.list-manage.com/track/click?u=099dfdaae98198ad83b0be7ba&amp;id=6fae82520b&amp;e=296833d790\" target=\"_blank\">https://survey.vovici.com/se.ashx?s=705E3ED0020246C1</a></h3>\n<h3 align=\"center\"> <b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">The Deadline to Complete this Survey isMay 1st</span></b></h3>\n<p align=\"center\"> <b>The NYC Department of Education seeks feedback to keep parents better informed about school quality. The DOE currently provides school quality information to parents through two main sources: the Progress Report and the Quality Review. The DOE is considering integrating this information with other sources to provide a better, more accurate picture of school quality to parents. </b><b>Your responses to the questions will help the DOE determine the best way to integrate and communicate this information in the future.  </b></p>\n<strong><span style=\"color: #008000\">Please take time to vote-daily!-for the Campos Children\'s Garden next door to school to get a Seeds of Change grant (see photo above--CWS got a grant last year to revitalize the garden after Hurricane Sandy and this grant will continue the work)-voting ends 21 April:</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #008000\">https://www.seedsofchangegrant.com/TheGallery.aspx?id=419692ac-246f-4219-97a6-b69f476e5261</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #000000\">Turtle Bay Music School\'s Saturday Music Project is now accepting applications for next school year 14/15:</span></strong>  Rising 3rd, 4th and 5th graders are encouraged to apply--free instrument instruction and music program on Saturdays.  Deadline is 7 June:\n\nhttp://www.tbms.org/saturday-music-project/\n\n<strong>National Children\'s Chorus audition<span style=\"color: #000000\">s</span></strong>--Thurs 1 May at Church of St Paul the Apostle by Columbus Circle, ages 5-16:  nationalchildrenschorus.com\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">S</span><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>c</strong>hools are Us:  Who Makes Decisions in Our Public Schools? is a flow chart created by the Center for Urban Pedagogy that explains the complicated  NYC public education system:  welcometocup.org</span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #800080\"><strong>Raffle!:  Win 2 tickets to see The Little Orchestra Society\'s production of Lemony Snickett\'s <em>The Composer is Dead</em> </strong></span>at Lincoln Center on Saturday 17 May at 11am.  $2 per chance/2 chances for $5.  Tickets on sale before Community Meeting on 2 May and 9 May-drawing 9 May at Community Meeting.\n\nLooking forward to the Fall--Mark your Calendars Now!:  <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>The Anna Howard Shaw School Building Centennial Celebration will be on Saturday 20 September</strong></span>--all 3 schools in our building (CWS, EVCS, PS94-The Spectrum School) will join together for a family-fun day to celebrate the 100th birthday of our school building!  To get involved, email ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #008000\">Esther\'s Half-Day Camp Club: karate, yoga, art projects on half- days--16 May, 3 June, 9 June--talk to Joyce to sign up.</span></strong>\n\n23 April--Community Education Council for District 1 meeting with special presentation on Special Education and IEPs--6pm at NEST+M dinner and childcare provided\n\n24 April--8am in lobby:  The Advocacy Committee will lead a discussion about the state tests\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\n\n<strong>3 May--Free Block Party and Birthday Cake Contest at Henry Street Settlement\n</strong>\n\nHenry Street is hosting a FREE block party to celebrate the 147th birthday of our founder, Lillian Wald, on <strong>Saturday, May 3, 2014</strong>, as part of Lower East Side History Month.\n\nThe party will be held at 265 Henry Street from noon to 3 p.m.\n\nActivities include a cake contest,* refreshments, music and dancing, arts activities for children, face-painting, blood pressure screenings, tours of the historic settlement house and more.\n\n</div>\n6 May-after drop-off at The Neighborhood School 121 East 3rd St:  Diversity Discussion--meeting to create a diversity policy to present to Chancellor Farina\n\n10 May--Art and Science Fair\n\n16 May: half day-12:10 pick up.  Bent on Learning and The Shala Yoga Studio will be honored at Community Meeting for bringing yoga to CWS kids\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">21 May:  PTA meeting at 6pm in lobby</span>\n\n24 May:  The Experimental Dance Group (EDG) will perform at The Theater for the New City at 2pm\n\n26 May--no school--Memorial Day--Hello Summer!\n\n30 May:  Schoolapalooza-- Lisa Lisa will perform!','20th Annual Art and Science Fair 10 May!  Schoolapalooza 30 May! and more...','','publish','open','open','','20th-annual-art-and-science-fair-10-may-schoolapalooza-30-may-and-more','','','2014-04-16 09:09:16','2014-04-16 13:09:16','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1216',0,'post','',0),(388,1,'2012-09-27 04:54:30','2012-09-27 04:54:30','','Print','','inherit','open','open','','print-4','','','2012-09-27 04:54:30','2012-09-27 04:54:30','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/shopbutton2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(424,1,'2012-09-28 03:22:16','2012-09-28 03:22:16','','CWSHEADING','','inherit','open','open','','cwsheading','','','2012-09-28 03:22:16','2012-09-28 03:22:16','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/CWSHEADING.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(401,1,'2012-09-27 06:21:41','2012-09-27 06:21:41','','Screen Shot 2012-09-27 at 1.23.46 AM','','inherit','open','open','','screen-shot-2012-09-27-at-1-23-46-am','','','2012-09-27 06:21:41','2012-09-27 06:21:41','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Screen-Shot-2012-09-27-at-1.23.46-AM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(402,1,'2012-09-27 06:22:20','2012-09-27 06:22:20','','Screen Shot 2012-09-27 at 1.23.20 AM','','inherit','open','open','','screen-shot-2012-09-27-at-1-23-20-am','','','2012-09-27 06:22:20','2012-09-27 06:22:20','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Screen-Shot-2012-09-27-at-1.23.20-AM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(413,1,'2012-09-27 06:50:17','2012-09-27 06:50:17','','CWSCookbook','','inherit','open','open','','cwscookbook','','','2012-09-27 06:50:17','2012-09-27 06:50:17','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/CWSCookbook.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1195,1,'2014-03-24 11:26:49','2014-03-24 15:26:49','<div>\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>FAMILIES INTERESTED IN THE CHILDREN’S WORKSHOP SCHOOL:  </strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>Our Last School Tours are on Fridays, March 28th, April 4th and April 11th at 9:00AM.</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>PLEASE EMAIL DOROTHY OR JOYCE TO SIGN UP:  dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov or jborden@schools.nyc.gov</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>We look forward to meeting you!</strong></span></p>\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"schoola auction itmes poster\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/schoola-auction-itmes-poster-194x300.jpg\" />\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMarcel is back in NYC for a limited engagement of one night. He and Frank (Franny\'s dad) will be playing at Chris\'s club, <strong>Brooklyn Rod &amp; Gun this evening, March 24<sup>th</sup> at 6:30 59 Kent Ave in Williamsburg</strong>. Adult donation at door $10 goes toward fifth grade yearbooks. Kids are free. The first show is for families. There will be a second session at 8:00 for adults and all parents who want to jam are welcome. Chris (Olive and Arlo\'s dad)  will donate part of bar sales as well.\n\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">Tues 25 March--Spring picture day!</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-family: arial;font-size: small;color: #339966\">Tues 25 March 4:45-8pm at Matilda on 11 St near Ave C--Fundraiser for Mr. Scott\'s Experimental Dance Group (EDG). $20 donation--sangria, delicious food and a disco trivia contest!</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #339966\"> </span></strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Weds 26 March at 8am in the Library: LETS TALK IN THE LIBRARY-WORKSHOP WITH DOROTHY - Common Core. Leveled books.. What does it mean when my child is reading \"Level M\" books? Accessing The Library Catalog from home. Also come in any time if you would like to talk to Dorothy or look at some of the non fiction texts that we have in our Library. 8:00 am is usually a quiet time!</span>\n\n</div>\n<div><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Thursday 27 March at 8:45 in the lobby: Workshop with Valerie Preston, our always dynamic and wise Pre K Social Worker on Developmental Stages, Understanding Your 4, 5, 6 Year Old</span></strong>\n<div>CWS After School Clubs presents: Half-Day Camp Club with Esther–karate, yoga, meditation, art projects at the school on the following half-days: May 16th, June 3rd and June 9th. Pick up at 5pm. $60/day. Please contact Joyce for full information. Please reserve early to save your child/ren spot.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial;font-size: small;color: #333399;text-decoration: underline\">Karate Club for Adults!!--Karate with Esther on Fridays 1:45-2:30--see Joyce in the office for full info!</span></strong></span></em></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Thanks to those who have been bringing in auction donations for Schoolapalooza--keep em coming!</div>\n</div>','Fifth-grade yearbook fundraiser tonight at Brooklyn Rod and Gun; Library Workshop with Dorothy-and more!','','publish','open','open','','fifth-grade-yearbook-fundraiser-tonight-at-brooklyn-rod-and-gun-library-workshop-with-dorothy-and-more','','','2014-03-24 11:26:49','2014-03-24 15:26:49','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1195',0,'post','',0),(1200,1,'2014-03-31 18:48:28','2014-03-31 22:48:28','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>FAMILIES INTERESTED IN THE CHILDREN’S WORKSHOP SCHOOL:  </strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>Our Last School Tour is on Friday April 11th at 9:00AM.</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>PLEASE EMAIL DOROTHY OR JOYCE TO SIGN UP:  dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov or jborden@schools.nyc.gov</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>We look forward to meeting you!</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1206\" alt=\"Schoola_call_2014_8\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Schoola_call_2014_8-200x300.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Thank you to the parents who volunteer in the office and library:</span>  Judy and Sayoko for helping Joyce in the office; late pass writers Nancy, Elizabeth, Susan, Amy and Judy; regular library volunteers Nicole, Lamont and Holly; and those who volunteered to help Dorothy organize and update the collection:  Nancy, Sean, Julie and Beth.  Dorothy also thanks the 4th graders on the Library Squad who are learning how to shelve books and help maintain the library\'s collection!\n\n<span style=\"color: #008080\">As always, thank you to the parents who contribute to Coffee And... every Friday:  Melissa for organizing it; Natalie, Roxanne, Sayoko, Paul and Beth--and to Porto Rico for donating their delicious coffee.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #993366\">Keep those donations coming in for Schoolapalooza!  </span>Save the date--30 May at Clemente Soto Velez Center--live music, great food, courtesy of Stephanie, art and silent auction. Thanks to Cassie for chairing, Rina, Tiffany, Evan, Williams, Kim, Rachel, and Mo for taking leadership roles on the Schoola committee.\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #33cccc\">CWS featured again in the United Federation of Teachers newspaper-</span>-</strong>Casey\'s class and Susan\'s class participated in a memorial for the victims of the Triangle Shirtwaist Fire:\n\nhttp://www.uft.org/news/remembering-legacy-triangle-shirtwaist-factory-fire\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #00ff00\">10 May--11-3pm Arts and Science Fair-fun for the whole family!</span> </strong> The scaffolding should be down by then and we shall celebrate!  Thanks to Judy for chairing, as always!  Email Judy to help out: garnar-wortzel@att.net\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Important Dates in April:</span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #333399\"><strong>2 April-PTA executive board meeting in lobby after drop-off</strong></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #339966\">9 April-General PTA meeting-after drop off in lobby</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #800080\">11 April--deadline for DOE parent surveys--visit Dorothy in the library if you have lost the green envelope given out at family conferences or are in need of internet access to take the survey online</span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">SPRING BREAK!! 14-22 April!  Back to school on 23 April!  </span></strong> If you need childcare over Spring Break, check out Green Apple Kids Camp .http://www.greenapplekidsny.com/\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #003300\">FUN STUFF TO DO OVER SPRING BREAK AND BEYOND</span></strong>\n\nMuseum of the City of New York: \"City as Canvas\"-graffiti art\n\nAmerican Museum of Natural History: \"The Power of Poison\" and \"Pterosaurus: Flight in the Age of Dinosaurs\"\n\nNew York Botanical Gardens-The Orchid Show\n\nWave Hill: Spring Vacation Week\n\nBrooklyn Children\'s Museum: \"Brooklyn Block Lab\"\n\nFREE!-New York Public Library (42 and 5th): \"The ABC of It: Why Children\'s Books Matter\"-extended til September!\n\nNew York Hall of Science: \"Human Plus: Real Lives and Real Engineering\"\n\nFREE: Central Park Charles A Dana Discovery Center (110 St and 5th Ave): \"Ponds, Pipes and People: Water in Central Park\"\n\nMuseum at Eldridge Street: Scavenger Hunt\n\nFREE: El Museo del Barrio: Super Sabado!--19 April\n\nFREE: Street Games-NYC Parks Dept Thomas Jefferson Park, 114 St and 1st Ave-26 April 11-3pm\n\nLiberty Science Center: \"Beyond Rubik\'s Cube\" starts 26 April til 30 June\n\nBrooklyn Botanical Gardens: Sakura Matsuri, the  Japanese Cherry Blossom Festival--26 and 27 April\n\nThe Morgan Library: \"The Little Prince\" Family Event --27 April\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">FUN AND (MOSTLY) AFFORDABLE SUMMER DAY CAMPS</span></strong>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Compiled by Dorothy, Beth, Roxanne and Karen and presented by Dorothy at the March PTA meeting:</p>\n<strong>University Settlement Cornerstone at Campos Plaza</strong>\nFree summer camp and after school activities, field trips, sports, homework help. See Dorothy for flyer.\n\n<strong>Sol Goldman 14th Street Y New Country Day Camp</strong>--buses take the kids to the beautiful Henry Kaufman Campgrounds in Staten Island for sports, swimming, activities.\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.14streety.org%2fnewcountry%2fnew-country-day-camp%2f\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.14streety.org/newcountry/new-country-day-camp/</a>\n\n<strong>Boys Club of New York Harriman Clubhouse</strong>--a neighborhood institution which provides recreational activities and academic support for boys. 287 East 10 St\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.bcny.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.bcny.org</a>\n\n<strong>Lower East Side Girls Club of NYC-</strong>-for girls 8-18: arts, sports, cultural and life skills programs.\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.girlsclub.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.girlsclub.org</a>\n\n<strong>City Sculpting</strong>--a creative visual arts program with a specialized focus on sculpture.\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fcitysculpting.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://citysculpting.com</a>\n\n<strong>Butter Beans Food &amp; Garden Summer Camp</strong> is a complete farm to table experience for campers ages 6-10, covering the full spectrum of the food cycle. We are excited to take amazing trips to the Brooklyn Grange, Battery Conservancy, Mother In Law\'s Kimchi, Foraging lead by Leda Meredith, Fine &amp; Raw Chocolates and Ample Hills Ice Cream. Camp runs from July 7th - August 22nd, in two week increments, and is located at 201 West 13th Street. To reserve your spot, email us at camp@butterbeanskitchen.com\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>Camp Henry:</strong> Henry Street Settlement\'s general day camp--6 weeks 7 July-15 Aug-can do one week or more-\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.henrystreet.org%2fprograms%2fyouth%2fsummer-day-camps.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.henrystreet.org/programs/youth/summer-day-camps.html</a></p>\n<strong>Abrons Arts Center Barbara L. Tate Arts Camp--a CWS family favorite!</strong> Held at the Henry St Settlement/Abrons Arts Center on Grand St: dance, acting, singing, art, weekly museum visits, weekly swimming. Ages 6 to 12. Early bird special if you register by 25 April. 10% discount for returning campers; 10% discount for siblings.\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.abronsartscenter.org%2fclasses-and-summer-programs%2fsummer-camps-and-classes.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.abronsartscenter.org/classes-and-summer-programs/summer-camps-and-classes.html</a>\n\n<strong>Oasis camp at PS110 on Delancey St</strong>--sports, swimming every day, arts, field trips\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.oasischildren.com%2fcamp.php%3fid%3d2\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.oasischildren.com/camp.php?id=2</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>Rod Rogers Dance Camp</strong>-all dance, all the time-info not out yet-on 4 st and 2 ave\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.rodrodgersdance.org%2ffall-winter-youth-program-13-14\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.rodrodgersdance.org/fall-winter-youth-program-13-14</a></p>\n<strong>Tada! Summer Week-Long Musical Theater Camps</strong>\n15 West 28 St\n$460 per week 9 June-29 Aug (less if more than 1 week)\nMon-Fri 9:30-2:30 kids rehearse all week and perform the show on Friday.\ntadatheater.com\n\n<strong>United Soccer Academy in McCarren Park in Williamsburg</strong>\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2funitedsocceracademy.com%2f\" target=\"_blank\">http://unitedsocceracademy.com/</a>\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.usasportgroup.com%2f\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.usasportgroup.com/</a>\n8:00AM until 3:00\nYou can sign up for one week or more, with a total of 4 weeks offered.\n\n<strong>Chelsea Piers</strong>\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.chelseapiers.com%2fcamp%2fsummer-camp%2fdates-tuition.cfm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.chelseapiers.com/camp/summer-camp/dates-tuition.cfm</a>\n\n<strong>Soccer/Swim Camp on West Side:</strong>\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.dusc.net%2fpages%2f\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.dusc.net/pages/</a>\n9:00-5:00\nPier 40, Hudson River &amp; Houston St.\n\n<strong>Mommypoppins Listings</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fmommypoppins.com%2fnew-york-summer-camp-guide\" target=\"_blank\">http://mommypoppins.com/new-york-summer-camp-guide</a>\n\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fmommypoppins.com%2fny-kids%2ffree-and-cheap-summer-camps\" target=\"_blank\">http://mommypoppins.com/ny-kids/free-and-cheap-summer-camps</a>\n\n<strong>Children\'s Advocacy Project Listings</strong>\n<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=80a4ed7ce5d6423194f5c2ae706358f8&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fcap4kids.org%2fnewyorkcity%2fparent-handouts%2fafter-school-camps-mentoring\" target=\"_blank\">http://cap4kids.org/newyorkcity/parent-handouts/after-school-camps-mentoring</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"></p>','News for April--Spring Break! and List of Summer Day Camps','','publish','open','open','','news-for-april-spring-break-and-list-of-summer-day-camps','','','2014-03-31 18:48:28','2014-03-31 22:48:28','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1200',0,'post','',0),(1173,1,'2014-03-14 07:40:10','2014-03-14 11:40:10','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">FAMILIES INTERESTED IN THE CHILDREN\'S WORKSHOP SCHOOL:  </span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Our Last School Tours are on Fridays, March 28th, April 4th and April 11th at 9:00AM.</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">PLEASE EMAIL DOROTHY OR JOYCE TO SIGN UP:  dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov or jborden@schools.nyc.gov</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">We look forward to meeting you!</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1174\" alt=\"schoola auction itmes poster\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/schoola-auction-itmes-poster-194x300.jpg\" width=\"194\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n\n<div><strong>Schoolapalooza will be on Friday, MAY 30th at The Clemente Soto Velez Center on the corner of Rivington and Suffolk Streets</strong>. We need you (and your stuff) for the fundraiser auction, which generates about $25,000 for our school\'s budget to help pay for everything from Turtle Bay Music to the CWS Band to Bent on Learning yoga.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div></div>\n<div>-Hit up your local businesses for gift certificates or merchandise: restaurants, stores, hair stylists!</div>\n<div>-Are you a photographer/teacher/knitter/handy person? Donate your services!</div>\n<div>-Do you or does someone in your family have a vacation home? These are very popular auction items. Donate a long weekend or a week!</div>\n<div>-Donate art! The great artists in our parent community make our auction special!</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Please bring in your donations of goods, services or gift certificates as soon as you can with the auction donation form filled out.  Extra auction forms at on the bulletin board in the lobby.   Leave auction items  with Joyce in the office or contact Rachel at <a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=bc3a5c9fb638411399dba6b68b8ae3e1&amp;URL=mailto%3arachiefrank515%40yahoo.com\">rachiefrank515@yahoo.com</a>, Tiffany at <a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=bc3a5c9fb638411399dba6b68b8ae3e1&amp;URL=mailto%3azergestiffany%40gmail.com\">zergestiffany@gmail.com</a>, or for ART contact Evan:<a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=bc3a5c9fb638411399dba6b68b8ae3e1&amp;URL=mailto%3aevan%40r20thcentury.com\">evan@r20thcentury.com</a>. For other auction-related questions, contact Cassy: <a href=\"https://mail.qcc.cuny.edu/owa/redir.aspx?C=bc3a5c9fb638411399dba6b68b8ae3e1&amp;URL=mailto%3aneyenesch%40yahoo.com\">neyenesch@yahoo.com</a>.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><em>Thank you to Cassy, Joyce, Rachel, Tiffany, Evan, Rina, Lori, Mo, Williams, Kim and Stephanie for their hard work planning Schoolapalooza.  If you want to get involved, email Cassy: neyenesch@yahoo.com</em></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>The Advocacy Committee of the PTA is running a meeting to discuss the issues around the state tests--directly after Community Meeting in the lobby-- today 14 March. </strong> Thank you to Hope, Julie, Eric, Jenny, KerriAnn, Nancy, Bryan and Kim for organizing this talk.  Other meetings to follow!</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Dorothy will be running a workshop on Weds 19 March at 8am to discuss the Common Core standards, as detailed in the  packet handed out by teachers at family conferences</strong>.  If you need another copy, download <strong>A Parent\'s Guide to the Common Core Standards</strong> here:</div>\n<div>http://nyspta.org/pdf/Advocacy/NYSPTA_NYSUT_Common_Core_Brochure_8.13.pdf</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>RAFFLE:  Win 2 tickets OR 3 tickets to see The Little Orchestra Society\'s production of <em>Hansel and Gretel</em> at Avery Fisher Hall,</strong> Lincoln Center on Sat 5 April at 11am.  $2 per chance/3 chances for $5.  Raffle tickets sold at Community Meetings--drawing will be 28 March at Community Meeting</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Save the date:  The Arts and Science Fair will be Saturday 10 May in the schoolyard!  </strong>Thanks, as always,  to Judy for chairing!</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>Our pre-k program is featured in The United Federation of Teachers NY Teacher publication!:</strong></span></div>\n<div><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>http://www.uft.org/feature-stories/lessons-build</strong></span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><em><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Please be sure to do NYC School Survey handed out at Family Conferences.  Take the survey online at:</span></strong></em></div>\n<div><em><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">nycschoolsurvey.org</span></strong></em></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><em><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Your survey access code is on the bottom right hand corner of the first page of the paper copy.  Any troubles, please contact Dorothy.</span></strong></em></div>\n<div><em><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Also, please take a survey about the survey by 21 March--see DOE explanation below:</span></strong></em></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<table cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div lang=\"EN-US\">\n\nThe New York City Department of Education is currently exploring ways to better inform parents about school quality, and we are reaching out for your assistance in obtaining feedback from parents about how they use this information to choose and assess schools. The Office of Research, Accountability, and Data have developed a short parent <a href=\"https://survey.vovici.com/se.ashx?s=705E3ED0020246C1\" target=\"_blank\">survey</a>, and we would appreciate your assistance with distributing the survey to parents and encouraging them to complete it.\n\nWe request that parents complete the survey by <b>March 21</b>. We also plan to conduct focus groups with parents on March 26 and April 3 to get more detailed feedback, and the survey asks if parents are available to participate in these sessions. We would welcome as many parents and guardians as can attend.\n\nYou can access the survey here: <a href=\"https://survey.vovici.com/se.ashx?s=705E3ED0020246C1\" target=\"_blank\">https://survey.vovici.com/se.ashx?s=705E3ED0020246C1</a>\n<div><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">CWS Clubs presents:  Half-Day Camp Club with Esther--karate, yoga, meditation, art projects at the school on the following half-days:  21 March, 16 May, 3 June and 9 June.  Pick up at 5pm.  Contact Joyce for full information.</span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Thanks to those of you who have attended our workshops and talks about testing, new standards and the Core Curriculum.A quick reminder from Dorothy  about upcoming dates…\nThis Friday, March 21st is a half day. Dismissal 12:10The NY State ELA exam will be given on April 1st, 2nd and 3rd (GRADES 3,4,5)The NY State MATH exam will be given April 31st, May 1ST and 2nd (GRADES 3,4,5)\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Workshop with Valerie Preston, Pre K Social Worker</span>\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Developmental Stages, Understanding 4, 5 and 6 Year olds. Tuesday March 25th 9:45 Lobby</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff\">LETS TALK IN THE LIBRARY - Common Core. Leveled books.. What does it mean when my child is reading \"Level M\" books? Accessing The Library Catalog from home - Wednesday March 26th, 8:00 am Library</span>\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div><span style=\"color: #008000\">Sat 29 March at PS20 (corner of Houston and Essex) from 9-12:30--Workshop for families in District 1 on School Diversity and Equity:</span></div>\n</div>\n<div><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=02517e0912&amp;view=att&amp;th=144e05ea42776d3e&amp;attid=0.1&amp;disp=emb&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1\" /></div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<table cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<table cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n<td rowspan=\"2\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\">\n<table cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div><b> </b></div>\n<div></div></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<table cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n<td><a href=\"https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?shva=1#ad,248\"> </a></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div></div></td>\n<td></td>\n<td>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div></div>\n<div>People (3)</div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n</div>','Schoolapalooza is Friday 30 May!  Call for Auction Items, Pre-K Class Featured in UFT Newspaper,  Common Core Workshop 19 March at 8am and Other News','','publish','open','open','','schoolapalooza-is-friday-30-may-call-for-auction-items-and-other-news','','','2014-03-14 07:40:10','2014-03-14 11:40:10','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1173',0,'post','',0),(427,1,'2012-09-28 03:30:01','2012-09-28 03:30:01','','FALL 2012 clubs list','','inherit','open','open','','fall-clubs-list-2012','','','2012-09-28 03:30:01','2012-09-28 03:30:01','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/FALL-clubs-list-2012-.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(428,1,'2012-09-28 03:31:09','2012-09-28 03:31:09','','EXTENDED LETTER FALL 2012','','inherit','open','open','','extended-letter-fall-2012','','','2012-09-28 03:31:09','2012-09-28 03:31:09','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/EXTENDED-LETTER-FALL-2012.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(1158,1,'2014-02-13 09:52:33','2014-02-13 14:52:33','Due to the snow, we are cancelling afterschool clubs and test prep today 13 Feb.\n\nFamilies can search the CWS Library collection online--thanks to Dorothy for running a mini-workshop at the PTA meeting last night.  Click on the Catalogue tap to search:\n\nibrary.nycenet.edu/common/servlet/presenthomeform.do?l2m=Home&amp;tm=Home&amp;l2m=Home\n\nIf this link does not work---try:\n\nhttp://www.tinyurl.com/visitthecwslibrary\n\nFamilies applying for kindergarten:  the DOE has extended the deadline to 20 Feb:\n\nhttp://schools.nyc.gov/ChoicesEnrollment/Elementary/Kindergarten\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Afterschool Clubs and Test Prep Cancelled for Today, 13 Feb/CWS Library website link/DOE Extends Kindergarten Application Deadline to 20 Feb','','publish','open','open','','afterschool-clubs-and-test-prep-cancelled-for-today-13-febcws-library-website-linkdoe-extends-kindergarten-application-deadline-to-20-feb','','','2014-02-13 09:52:33','2014-02-13 14:52:33','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1158',0,'post','',0),(1161,1,'2014-02-16 18:50:25','2014-02-16 23:50:25','<span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Fun Stuff to Do Over February Break 15-23 Feb:</span>\n\nFREE!--\"Ladies and Gentlemen...The Beatles!\" exhibit at The New York Public Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center--11 Feb til 10 May\n\nFREE!  Urban Park Rangers Kids Week Events--at park locations all over the city:\n\nhttp://www.nycgovparks.org/events/urbanparkrangers\n\nFREE:  New York Public Library main branch on 42nd and 5th:  The ABC of It:  Why Children\'s Books Matter\n\nFREE: The Schomberg Center for Research in Black Culture--2 exhibits--Motown: The Truth is a Hit and Funky Turns 40:  Black Character Revolution\n\nEngineering Week at The New York Hall of Science--make slime! build a rocket!\n\nNew Space Show at the Museum of Natural History--Dark Universe, narrated by Neil DeGrasse Tyson and special exhibit:  The Power of Poison\n\nThe Little Prince:  A New York Story at The Morgan Library 24 Jan-27 April\n\nNew York Botanical Garden:  Culinary Kids Food Festival --activities all week\n\nGraffiti art exhibit \"City as Canvas\" at The Museum of the City of New York\n\n\"Indie Essentials:  25 Must-Play Video Games\" at The Museum of the Moving Image\n\nKids Week at The Intrepid--activities all week long\n\nIce skate!:  Bryant Park, Prospect Park, South Street Seaport\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Back to school 24 February!</span>\n\nOur beautiful  library will be closed all week for Dorothy and parent volunteers Lamont, Nicole and Holly to update the collection.  If you can help out one day, please email Dorothy: dcantwell2@childrensworkshopschool.org\n\nCongrats to Darryl LaVare, CWS mom and leader of the Painting and Mural Clubs, who has a show of her paintings at the Micheal Mut Project Space, 97 Avenue C, from 27 Feb til 29 March.  Reception Thurs 27 Feb 6-8pm.\n\nAlso on Thurs 27 Feb, starting at 6pm in the auditorium:  The EVCS Parent Association is hosting a special meeting on the topic of gender expression, led by Jean Malpas, director of the Gender and Families Project at the Ackerman Institute for the Family.  RSVP to parents@evcsnyc.org\n\n<em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #ff6600;text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #008080;text-decoration: underline\"><strong>Friday 28 February:  half day!--12:10 dismissal</strong> <span style=\"color: #000000;text-decoration: underline\">and </span></span></span></span></em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #ff6600\"><span style=\"color: #000000;text-decoration: underline\">the third graders will perform their MLK Celebration skits at Community Meeting. Also--it\'s Crayola Storm Day!</span></span></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Families interested in The Children\'s Workshop School:  Please email Joyce jborden@schools.nyc.gov  or Dorothy dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov  to sign up to attend a school tour, held on the following Friday mornings at 9am:  28 Feb, 7 March, 14 March.  We look forward to meeting you!</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nI\n\n&nbsp;','Fun Stuff to Do Over February Break----Back to School News--More School Tour Dates','','publish','open','open','','what-to-do-over-february-break-newsreminders-more-school-tour-dates','','','2014-02-16 18:50:25','2014-02-16 23:50:25','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1161',0,'post','',0),(1168,1,'2014-02-28 15:12:54','2014-02-28 20:12:54','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/22fb0e172fd6d94c84cac8bcd/images/EDGee215c.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"256\" align=\"center\" /></p>\n<strong>Important Dates in March:</strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: tahoma\"><strong><strong>Friday March 7th--Martin Luther King Celebration at Community Meeting continues with performances by the 3/4/5, fourth, and fifth graders</strong></strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: tahoma\"><strong>Tuesday, March 11:  Half day for afternoon family conference - 11:30am pick up - NO CLUBS</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: tahoma\"><strong>Wednesday, March 12: PTA Meeting in lobby after drop-off.  Evening family conferences - 3:00pm pick up - NO CLUBS</strong></span>\n\nFriday, March 21: Half day for teacher professional development - 12:10pm pick up - NO CLUBS\n\n<span style=\"font-family: tahoma\"><strong>Thursday March 27:  pre-k non attendance day</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #008080\"><strong>Anna Howard Shaw School Building Centennial Celebration Planning Meeting-</strong>-<strong>Tues 18 March in library conference room after drop-off:</strong>  Our school building is 100 years old!  In September, all 3 schools:  CWS, EVCS and The Spectrum School will celebrate both the centennial of the building and the removal of the scaffolding with a big party!  If you would like to be involved, email ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">Valerie, our pre-k social worker, will lead a workshop on Understanding Developmental Stages after drop-off on 25 March!</span></strong>\n<table width=\"100%\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<table width=\"600\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"left\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\"><strong>You are cordially invited to the second fundraiser for Mr. Scott\'s dance company The Experimental Dance Group at Matilda, owned by CWS family Maristella, Esteban and Matilda. Your $20 donation will include a complimentary drink as well as assorted appetizers which include: fried calamari, quesadilla, and pizza. What a wonderful way to have fun after work and all for a good cause while listening to real disco music. Don\'t forget to participate in the disco trivia contest to win an E.D.G. T-shirt! See you there. </strong><strong>Where: Matilda Restaurant 647 East 11th Street (between Ave B and Ave C)</strong>\n<strong>When: March 25th, 2014</strong>\n<strong>Time: 4:45 pm to 8:00 pm</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width=\"100%\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<table width=\"100%\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"left\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/22fb0e172fd6d94c84cac8bcd/images/dirty_wars_soshe336f8.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" align=\"center\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Congratulations to CWS parent David Riker (Maria and alum Laila\'s  dad!) who co-wrote the screenplay</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong> to the Oscar-nominated documentary Dirty Wars. </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/22fb0e172fd6d94c84cac8bcd/images/schoola.jpg\" width=\"499\" align=\"center\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">The Children\'s Workshop School\'s annual evening fundraiser Schoolapalooza is on May 30th at the Clemente Soto Velez Center!!  To volunteer to help out, email ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Thank you to Cassy for being the Schoola Chair!</span></strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','News for March:  Family Conferences, Experimental Dance Group Fundraiser at Matilda, Understanding Developmental Stages Workshop with Valerie','','publish','open','open','','news-for-march-family-conferences-experimental-dance-group-fundraiser-at-matilda-understanding-developmental-stages-workshop-with-valerie','','','2014-02-28 15:12:54','2014-02-28 20:12:54','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1168',0,'post','',0),(913,1,'2013-08-09 12:41:49','2013-08-09 16:41:49','[caption id=\"attachment_918\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-918 aligncenter\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/photo-300x224.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"224\" /> Spring 2013 Let\'s Paint a Mural Club\'s Mural at Campos Garden[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>The Children’s Workshop School Update</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong></strong><strong>For Back-to-School 2013</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://www.childrensworkshopschool.org/\">http://www.childrensworkshopschool.org</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">212-614-9531 or <a href=\"mailto:ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org\">ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">”We’re all a family under one sky!”</p>\n<strong>For prospective families:  </strong>Looking for a kindergarten spot for your child?  We still have a limited number of kindergarten seats for the 2013/2014 school year.  Limited seats are available in grades 1-4 as well.  Due to construction, our school office will not be open until 25 August.  Please email Dorothy, our parent coordinator, with your information to find out how to go about applying for these seats: <a href=\"mailto:dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov\">dcantwell2@schools.nyc.gov</a>.  If you are looking for a pre-kindergarten or kindergarten spot for next school year, 2014/2015 please check our website, childrensworkshopschool.org, in September for tour dates, which will begin in October.\n\n<strong>For all members of the CWS community: </strong> Get on the bus!  <strong>Join the 50<sup>th</sup> Anniversary of the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, where MLK gave his “I Have a Dream” speech that inspired Maria and Jean to found our school.  Saturday 24 August</strong>—buses leave for Washington DC at 4 am. Email Beth for transportation info: c<a href=\"mailto:co-president1@childrensworkshopschool.org\">o-president1@childrensworkshopschool.org</a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #800080\"> <strong>Welcome to new and returning families!</strong>  <strong>Here’s what you need to know for back-to-school—and other news:</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong><em>Teacher letters are set to go out in the mail on 20 August.</em></strong></span>\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong><span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>The auditorium will be finished!</strong>  </span>Thanks to the team of renovators, we will once again hold our weekly Friday Community Meetings in the auditorium but now with state-of-the-art sound and light system, all-new stage, seating, floor, ceiling.  We all must observe a new rule:  no food or drink allowed in the auditorium, ever.  See our website, childrensworkshopschool.org, for photos taken by Joyce in July—it looks amazing!\n\nWe will also have <strong>Smartboards</strong> and a new set of laptops from a RESO-A grant—thanks to the Tech Team (made up of parents and teachers) for their hard work and Councilwoman Rosie Mendez for her constant support of our school.  We won another RESO-A grant so that for next school year (14/15), we will have Smartboards in every classroom.\n\n<strong>Congrats to Chris</strong>—he is officially our new Building Manager.  Also, thanks to Hope’s tireless advocacy, we will <strong>continue to have two school safety officers, Officer Baptiste and Officer Das.</strong>\n\n<strong> </strong><strong>Baby news:</strong>  Michelle M. had a baby girl, Alexa Rose and Michelle F. had twins (!):  Matthew and Mason.  Congrats to both families!\n\n<strong><em>Afterschool Clubs will start Monday 16 September—thanks to Joyce, Rachel and Daryl! Here\'s the Fall Club offerings--please note that Darryl\'s Painting Projects Club on Monday, her Let\'s Paint a Mural Club on Weds and Patrizia\'s Dance Improvisation Club on Thursdays are all open to grades 1-5:</em></strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/cws-fall-13-clubs1.pdf\">http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/cws-fall-13-clubs1.pdf</a>\n\n<strong><em>If you can help out with Afterschool Clubs registration on the mornings of 11 and 12 September, please email Rachel: </em></strong> <a href=\"mailto:Rachel@dancewithrachel.com\">Rachel@dancewithrachel.com</a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>FIRST WEEK OF SCHOOL:</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>9 Sept:</strong></span>  <strong>first day of school –half day for pre-k and k; full day for grades 1-5.  Pre-k and k drop off in their classrooms; for grades 1-5 drop-off and pick up will continue to be in the lobby.  <em>Look for Dorothy, our parent coordinator, in the lobby after drop-off for help with questions and to give separation-anxiety comfort.</em></strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>10 Sept</strong>:</span>  <strong>half-day for pre-k; full day for k-5—Dorothy will again be in the lobby after drop-off</strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>11 Sept:</strong></span>  <strong>full day for all students.  Afterschool Clubs registration in the lobby in the morning.  No need to rush to be first in line; if a club is overenrolled, it goes to a lottery. Clubs start Monday 16 September.  See Fall 13 Afterschool Clubs offerings on our website, childrensworkshopschool.org</strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">12 Sept:</span> Afterschool Clubs registration continues in the lobby in the morning.</strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong><em>13 Sept:  All-Family Welcome Breakfast and PTA Meeting in the lobby after drop-off.  Meet the PTA Executive Board and find out the many ways you can get involved at CWS!</em></strong></span>\n\nEnjoy the rest of your summer!  Any questions/concerns/ideas please email <a href=\"mailto:ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org\">ptaeb@childrensworkshopschool.org</a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','CWS Back to School Update!','','publish','open','open','','cws-back-to-school-update','','','2013-08-09 12:41:49','2013-08-09 16:41:49','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=913',0,'post','',0),(993,1,'2013-10-18 14:38:33','2013-10-18 18:38:33','Today, we held the first Co