ool.org/?p=621',0,'post','',0),(711,1,'2012-11-06 08:00:29','2012-11-06 13:00:29','Elyssa’s kindergarten class and Michelle F.’s 1st and 2nd Grade class are coordinating this year’s Penny Harvest—bring bags of pennies and change to your child’s classroom—all the change gathered will be collected, then students will research, discuss and decide which organization to donate to. Our Kindergarten class is one of the youngest coordinators leading the harvest in NYC.\n\nFor those of you who do not know about the year long Penny Harvest: Please check the <a href=\"http://www.commoncents.org/go/penny-harvest\">Common Cents website.</a> \"The Penny Harvest encourages a caring culture and sense of belonging; we see it as an opportunity to enhance curriculum through a blend of service-learning, character education, and child philanthropy; community leaders value the millions of dollars and hours that children donate back to better our communities; and kids like the program because it’s fun!  \"\n\n<a href=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?attachment_id=713\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-713\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-713\" title=\"pennyharvest-logo\" src=\"http://childrensworkshopschool.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Picture-24-300x61.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"61\" /></a>\n&nbsp;','Penny Harvest','','pending','open','open','','','','','2012-11-06 08:00:29','2012-11-06 13:00:29','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=711',0,'post','',0),(1149,1,'2014-02-10 16:33:24','2014-02-10 21:33:24','','CWS Book Fair at Barnes and Noble','','private','open','open','','cws-book-fair-at-barnes-and-noble','','','2014-02-10 16:33:24','2014-02-10 21:33:24','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1149',0,'post','',0),(1301,1,'2014-07-07 16:13:02','2014-07-07 20:13:02','<strong>HISTORY OF OUR LIBRARY</strong>By Dorothy Cantwell\nIt was 1998. Although I worked full time I, like many parents, was also committing time and energy to volunteering at the school my children attended, The Children’s Workshop School (CWS), a public elementary school in Manhattan’s Lower East Side. I was naïve and absolutely dismayed to learn that the school did not have a library! As a child, I had spent hours in the school library, where my love of reading was encouraged and nourished and I simply couldn’t imagine a school without one.  I made it my mission to make sure that the children of CWS could have the same invaluable experience as I had and, with the formal approval of the principal, Maria Velez-Clarke, The PTA and the School Leadership Team, I formed a committee to explore and research funding sources to create what I believed to be essential to any child‘s education.\nThis was the beginning of a 4 year project which resulted in the creation of The Children’s Workshop School Library, which now has a collection of over 10,000 beautifully kept books, and is filled with children every day. The benefits of my involvement in this project to me personally, were immeasurable. I learned so much during those years about the value of libraries, the history and dismantling of school libraries in New York City, and the struggle and challenges that educators faced trying to bring them back into the lives of children who need them most. I also received an amazing education about library design, technology, automation, collection building and curriculum.\nThe CWS Library Committee included administrators, teachers and parents. We established a weekly meeting schedule and prepared ourselves for a long project. We began with site visits to schools fortunate enough to have libraries, to try to form a vision of what we wanted for the school. We were very happy to get great advice form principals including Dr Leonard Golubchick (PS 20) and Anne Cooke (The Urban Academy).  I set up advisory relationships with certified librarians, the School Library Services, architects and technology experts, and formed sub committees to develop goals. After we had written a mission, a vision statement and a list of features we wanted to include in the library, we reached out to Margarita Lopez, then City Councilwoman, to request funding for the project. To say we were amazed and grateful when she awarded us with a $450,000 grant… is an understatement.  District One Superintendent Helen Santiago approved 3 adjoining classrooms on the 4th floor, which was unoccupied at the time. Dr. Paul Loughran, D01 Deputy Superintendent, served as a liaison to the DOE and gave us the go ahead.\n We were ecstatic, and began the work of developing our plan with a wonderful architect, Selim Ozalp from the Division of School Facilities and began a series of discussions with him and Project Manager Barry Apple about the design and construction. It was most important to us that the library reflected our educational philosophy and that the teachers and librarian would be able to conduct lessons in the same way they were able to in the classrooms. We wanted to be able to provide full group instruction, small group work and independent reading. The final design was perfect and included a storytelling area, tables for group work and listening center, smaller nooks for children to read quietly and a small conference room for meetings and laptop instruction. Working with librarians, book vendors and Carol Ray, who would become the librarian, we developed and purchased our start up collection. And lastly, we set up an automated circulation and catalogue (Winnebago Spectrum).  During the years that Carol was the librarian, she built the collection to what it is today, a rich and eclectic variety of superb and rare children’s books which reflect not only the traditions of classical children’s literature, and the life changing social history which brought us together, but the diversity of the children and the world we share. Carol initiated the Living the Dream Award, a collaboration between 5th graders from The Children’s Workshop School, and Manhattan Country School, during which the students read and discuss 10 books published that year and then vote to honor the book that most embodies the dreams and vision of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. \nThe library opened in 2001 with a celebration and a special news story on NY1 about our struggle and success. The shelves filled with books and Children’s Workshop School classes began to use the library, The year also brought another school into the building. The East Village Community School (formerly the Lower East Side School), moved onto the 4th floor, and students began to visit the library with their teachers to enjoy and borrow books. Classes from The Spectrum School (PS 94) a District 75 Program also spend time in the Library and circulate books. Although when we started the project we did not know who would be sharing the building, or if indeed we would expand to become a K-8 School, it was always a given that all children in the building would have access.\n Now, almost 600 students use the library on a full week. CWS students either visit the library with Out of Classroom Support Teachers, Noelle or Kimberly as a part of their literacy curriculum or with their classroom teachers for read aloud, targeted instruction, author and genre studies, or research. Information literacy is woven into the curriculum and aligned with The Empire State Information Fluency Curriculum http://schools.nyc.gov/NR/rdonlyres/1A931D4E-1620-4672-ABEF-460A273D0D5F/0/EmpireStateIFC.pdf .Students from the East Village Community School visit with their classroom teachers, and may use the time for working on research projects, individual or partnered reading, themed read a loud and class discussions often connected to the classroom units of study. The Spectrum School Teachers visit with small groups, reading with the students and often making use of the books on tape. For all schools, part of the period is reserved for browsing, reading quietly and circulating books. \nI manage the library, arrange the schedule for the classes and for the conference room, which is used for PTA, SLT, Committee meetings and small workshops. If requested, I support the teachers with lessons on library and research skills.  I facilitate the circulation of books using the Destiny System, a city wide automation program which was purchased by the CWS PTA in 2012 and I train parents and teachers to use the system from home or classroom. www.tinyurl.com/VISITTHECWSLIBRARY . I select and process new books which are purchased with NYSTL funds from CWS and EVCS or are donated by friends and alumni. In addition, The CWS PTA holds a Barnes and Noble Bookfair each year to raise money to add to the library collection. I am fortunate to have team of parent volunteers to assist with maintenance of the library and collection. Last year we began a 4th grade Library Squad. In 2014, we plan to implement an Early Morning Family Reading Series for CWS families one morning a week. \nAlso planned for 2014 is an Author Series. We will keep you posted!','History of the CWS Library','','private','open','open','','history-of-the-cws-library','','','2014-07-07 16:13:02','2014-07-07 20:13:02','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1301',0,'post','',0),(1331,1,'2014-07-09 15:07:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Interested in the Children\'s Workshop School?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-07-09 15:07:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1331',0,'post','',0),(1,1,'2012-09-24 08:15:11','2012-09-24 08:15:11','Childcare provided. Please bring your child to the Cafeteria through the school yard. 6pm ~ 8pm.','9/24/2012 Curriculum Night tonight','','publish','open','open','','hello-world','','','2012-09-24 08:15:11','2012-09-24 08:15:11','',0,'http://childrensworkshopschool.org/?p=1',0,'post','',0),(11,1,'2012-09-20 09:00:19','2012-09-20 09:00:19','Thank you for coming to the PTA meeting! The turn out was great! 60 plus parents and teachers! And thank you for signing up for